VALUES
(43, 7, 12, 40, 10, 25, 25, 'deceiveth the people', 'Perception of Jesus and His Followers', 'Both passages emphasize the division in public opinion about Jesus. In John 7:12, some view him as a good man while others see him as deceiving the people, paralleling Matthew 10:25, which suggests that if Jesus is called Beelzebub, his followers will face similar accusations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 40, 16, 13, 16, 'He is a good man', 'Public Perception of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize differing opinions about Jesus. In John 7:12, some view him as a good man, while in Matthew 16:13-16, the disciples report various identities attributed to him, reflecting the confusion and debate surrounding his true nature.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 42, 6, 45, 45, 'He is a good man', 'Goodness and Deception Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between a good man and one who deceives. John 7:12 presents conflicting views on Jesus'' character, while Luke 6:45 explains that a good man brings forth good from his heart. This connection highlights the moral evaluation of individuals based on their actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 42, 7, 16, 16, 'He is a good man', 'Perception of Jesus as Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s reactions to Jesus, with some viewing him as a good man and others as a deceiver. In Luke, the acknowledgment of Jesus as a great prophet reflects a similar division in opinion found in John.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 12, 44, 11, 24, 24, 'He is a good man', 'Good Man Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the characterization of a ''good man.'' In John 7:12, some people debate whether Jesus is a good man, while Acts 11:24 explicitly describes Barnabas as a good man, highlighting a positive perception of his character.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 43, 9, 22, 22, 'fear of the Jews', 'Fear of the Jews', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the Jews, which leads individuals to silence about Jesus. In John 7:13, the fear prevents open discussion, while in John 9:22, it causes the parents to deny their son''s confession of Christ.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 43, 19, 38, 38, 'for fear of the Jews', 'Fear of the Jews', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the Jews that led to secrecy in the actions of Jesus'' followers. In John 7:13, people spoke openly about Jesus only with fear, while in John 19:38, Joseph of Arimathea acted secretly for the same reason.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 20, 29, 25, 25, 'fear of the Jews', 'Fear and Trust in God', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in both passages. John 7:13 mentions fear of the Jews, while Proverbs 29:25 states that ''the fear of man bringeth a snare,'' contrasting it with trust in the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 48, 2, 12, 13, NULL, 'Fear of Social Repercussions', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear influencing behavior. In John 7:13, fear of the Jews prevents open discussion about Jesus, while in Galatians 2:12-13, fear of the circumcision leads Peter to withdraw from Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 55, 2, 9, 13, 'fear of the Jews', 'Fear and Suffering for Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering for faith. In John 7:13, fear of the Jews leads to silence about Jesus, while 2 Timothy 2:9-13 discusses enduring suffering for the sake of the Gospel. Both passages emphasize the challenges faced by believers in proclaiming their faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 13, 66, 2, 13, 13, 'for fear of the Jews', 'Fear and Faith Amidst Persecution', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in the face of persecution, as seen in John 7:13 where people spoke ''for fear of the Jews.'' Similarly, Revelation 2:13 acknowledges the faithfulness of believers despite the presence of ''Satan''s seat'' and the martyrdom of Antipas. Both passages emphasize the struggle of maintaining faith amidst societal pressures.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 14, 43, 7, 28, 28, 'taught', 'Jesus Teaching in the Temple', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' active role in teaching during the feast, as noted in both passages. The emphasis on his teaching in the temple underscores his authority and the revelation of his true identity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 14, 42, 19, 47, 47, NULL, 'Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' teaching in the temple. In John 7:14, he begins teaching during a feast, while in Luke 19:47, he continues to teach daily, indicating a consistent presence and message in the temple.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 14, 43, 8, 2, 2, 'taught', 'Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' teaching in the temple. In John 7:14, he begins teaching during the feast, and in John 8:2, he continues this teaching the next morning, highlighting his role as a teacher.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 14, 4, 29, 12, 13, 'the feast', 'Feast and Teaching Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of a feast. John 7:14 describes Jesus teaching during a festival, while Numbers 29:12-13 outlines the observance of a holy convocation during a feast.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 14, 37, 2, 7, 9, 'taught', 'Jesus and the Glory of the Temple', 'This connection highlights the theme of glory associated with the temple. In John 7:14, Jesus teaches in the temple, while Haggai 2:7-9 speaks of the glory that will fill the house, linking Jesus'' presence to the fulfillment of this prophecy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 14, 39, 3, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection to Jesus in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize the temple as a significant location for divine revelation. In Malachi, the Lord is said to come to His temple, while in John, Jesus teaches in the temple during the feast.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 14, 40, 21, 12, 12, 'into the temple', 'Jesus in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' actions in the temple. In John, He teaches in the temple, while in Matthew, He demonstrates authority by casting out merchants.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 15, 42, 4, 22, 22, 'marvelled, saying, How knoweth this man letters', 'Wonder at Jesus'' Knowledge', 'Both passages emphasize the amazement of the people at Jesus'' words and knowledge. In John, they marvel at how he knows letters, while in Luke, they wonder at his gracious words.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 15, 40, 7, 28, 29, 'How knoweth this man letters', 'Authority in Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the astonishment of the people at Jesus'' teaching. In John, they marvel at his knowledge despite his lack of formal education, while in Matthew, they are astonished at his authoritative teaching compared to the scribes.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 15, 40, 13, 54, 54, 'marvelled, saying, How knoweth this man letters', 'Astonishment at Jesus'' Wisdom', 'Both passages emphasize the astonishment of the people at Jesus'' wisdom and teachings. In John, they marvel at how he knows letters, while in Matthew, they are astonished by his wisdom and mighty works.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 15, 42, 2, 47, 47, 'marvelled, saying, How knoweth this man letters', 'Astonishment at Understanding', 'Both passages emphasize the astonishment of listeners at Jesus'' profound understanding. In John, the Jews marvel at His knowledge, while in Luke, the audience is astonished at His understanding and answers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 15, 43, 7, 46, 46, 'How knoweth this man letters', 'Authority of Jesus'' Teaching', 'This connection highlights the astonishment of the Jews at Jesus'' knowledge and the officers'' recognition of His unique authority in teaching. Both passages emphasize the extraordinary nature of Jesus'' words and understanding, suggesting a profound impact on those who heard Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 15, 44, 26, 24, 24, NULL, 'Learning and Perception of Madness', 'This connection highlights the theme of how learning is perceived by others. In both passages, the idea of ''much learning'' leads to astonishment or accusations of madness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 15, 30, 7, 14, 15, 'How knoweth this man letters', 'Connection of Unlearned Prophets', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals who are not formally educated yet are called to deliver God''s message. Both Jesus and Amos are recognized for their profound understanding despite their lack of traditional training.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 16, 43, 14, 10, 10, 'not mine, but his that sent me', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize that Jesus'' teachings and actions are not his own but come from the Father. This connection highlights the unity between Jesus and the Father in their divine mission.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 16, 43, 5, 30, 30, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that Jesus'' actions and teachings are not his own but are derived from the Father who sent him. This connection highlights the theme of divine authority and obedience to God''s will.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 16, 43, 17, 8, 8, 'my doctrine is not mine', 'Connection of Divine Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the source of Jesus'' teachings. In John 7:16, Jesus states that his doctrine is from the one who sent him, while in John 17:8, he conveys the words given to him by the Father.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 16, 43, 3, 11, 11, 'my doctrine is not mine', 'Connection of Witness and Doctrine', 'Both passages emphasize the source of knowledge and testimony. In John 7:16, Jesus indicates that his doctrine comes from the one who sent him, while in John 3:11, he speaks of testifying to what they know and have seen.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 16, 66, 1, 1, 1, 'my doctrine is not mine', 'Connection of Divine Revelation', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine teaching. Both passages emphasize that the doctrine and revelation come from God, with Jesus indicating his teachings are from the one who sent him.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
